All archives use the GCC/Clang archive format and are linkable by the
gcc-family toolchains that cgo drives. MSVC-produced .lib files are NOT
shipped here because cgo on Windows uses gcc, not cl.exe — the Windows
slice is built with MSYS2 mingw-w64-x86_64.

Link order
----------
cgo's LDFLAGS must list the wrapper first (most-dependent) and the RNG
primitives last (least-dependent) so each archive resolves the next's
unresolved references in a single left-to-right pass:

  #cgo CPPFLAGS: -I${SRCDIR}/third_party/evi/include
  #cgo darwin  LDFLAGS: -L${SRCDIR}/third_party/evi/<goos>_<goarch>/lib \
                        -levi_c_api -levi_crypto -ldeb -lalea \
                        -L/opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/lib \
                        -L/usr/local/opt/openssl@3/lib \
                        -lssl -lcrypto -lc++ -lm
  #cgo linux   LDFLAGS: -L${SRCDIR}/third_party/evi/<goos>_<goarch>/lib \
                        -levi_c_api -levi_crypto -ldeb -lalea \
                        -lssl -lcrypto -lstdc++ -lm
  #cgo windows LDFLAGS: -L${SRCDIR}/third_party/evi/<goos>_<goarch>/lib \
                        -levi_c_api -levi_crypto -ldeb -lalea \
                        -lssl -lcrypto -lstdc++ -lm

darwin uses libc++ (Apple default), linux/MinGW use libstdc++.

OpenSSL is required even on the NONE-seal path. `evi_seal_info_create`
(called by MultiKeyGenerator and Decryptor) transitively pulls
`AES.cpp.o` + `Utils.cpp.o` into the link, and those `.o` members
reference `BIO_*`, `EVP_*`, `RAND_*`. On macOS the Homebrew openssl@3
prefix differs between Apple Silicon (/opt/homebrew) and Intel
(/usr/local) — both search paths are supplied; the linker warns but
continues for the non-existent one. Linux assumes system `libssl-dev`
(Debian/Ubuntu) or `openssl-devel` (RHEL/Fedora). Windows assumes
MSYS2 `mingw-w64-x86_64-openssl`.

