How to refresh
--------------
1. Clone or update CryptoLabInc/evi-crypto locally.
2. Run `scripts/refresh-evi.sh <path-to-evi-crypto-checkout>` from the repo root.
3. The script cmake-builds for the current host and copies all four static
   archives (libevi_c_api.a, libevi_crypto.a, libdeb.a, libalea.a) plus
   headers into this tree.
4. Update the "Pinned commit" line above with the evi-crypto commit hash.
5. Regenerate the SHA256 tables below via
   `shasum -a 256 <goos>_<goarch>/lib/*.a` and
   `shasum -a 256 evi-crypto-*.tar.gz`.
6. Commit the changed archives + this file in the same PR.

Multi-platform refresh via CI
-----------------------------
`scripts/refresh-evi.sh` only covers the current host. To refresh every
platform in one shot, use the upstream release workflow:

1. In evi-crypto, trigger `.github/workflows/release.yml` (tag push `v*`
   or manual `workflow_dispatch`).
2. Download evi-crypto-<goos>_<goarch>.tar.gz for each of
   linux_amd64, linux_arm64, darwin_amd64, darwin_arm64, windows_amd64.
3. Extract each archive and copy all four `lib/*.a` files
   (libevi_c_api.a, libevi_crypto.a, libdeb.a, libalea.a) into
   `third_party/evi/<goos>_<goarch>/lib/`. Do not copy any shared
   libraries (.so / .dylib / .dll / .dll.a) — the SDK contract is
   static-only.
4. Copy `include/` from any one *nix archive into `third_party/evi/include/`
   — headers are source-level and bit-identical across Unix artifacts.
   (If windows_amd64 is your only source, strip CRLF first; MSYS2 tar
    preserves LF so this is unlikely to matter in practice.)
5. Refresh the SHA256 tables below and bump the "Pinned commit" line.

